	{
		name: "std/base64",
		namespace: "base64",
		blocks: [
			{
				kind: "p",
				text: "Base64 encoding for `bytes`: packing raw bytes into a text string made of letters, digits, and a couple of symbols, so binary data can ride safely through things that only handle text -- email, JSON, URLs.",
			},
			{
				kind: "p",
				text: "There are two flavors: - `encode` / `decode` use the standard alphabet (with `+` and `/`)",
			},
			{
				kind: "code",
				text: "and `=` padding. This is what most APIs, email, and OpenSSL expect.",
			},
			{
				kind: "p",
				text: "- `url-encode` / `url-decode` use the URL-safe alphabet (`-` and `_`",
			},
			{
				kind: "code",
				text: "in place of `+` and `/`) with no padding, so the result is safe to\ndrop straight into a URL or a filename. JWTs use this form.",
			},
			{
				kind: "p",
				text: "Both decoders accept input with or without the trailing `=` padding, and reject any character outside the chosen alphabet.",
			},
		],
		items: [
			{
				name: "encode",
				signature: "bytes -> string",
				blocks: [
					{
						kind: "p",
						text: "Encodes bytes with the standard alphabet, including `=` padding.",
					},
					{kind: "code", text: "base64.encode 'hello'   # => \"aGVsbG8=\""},
				],
			},
			{
				name: "url-encode",
				signature: "bytes -> string",
				blocks: [
					{kind: "p", text: "Encodes bytes with the URL-safe alphabet and no padding."},
					{kind: "code", text: "base64.url-encode 'hello'   # => \"aGVsbG8\""},
				],
			},
			{
				name: "decode",
				signature: "string -> result bytes string",
				blocks: [
					{
						kind: "p",
						text: "Decodes a standard-alphabet base64 string back into bytes. The trailing padding is optional.",
					},
					{kind: "code", text: "base64.decode \"aGVsbG8=\"   # => ok 'hello'"},
				],
			},
			{
				name: "url-decode",
				signature: "string -> result bytes string",
				blocks: [
					{
